A '''medical certificate''' (sometimes referred to as a '''doctor's certificate'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.workplaceinfo.com.au/payroll/leave/employers-should-not-question-doctors-certificates-ama |title=Employers should not question a doctor’s certificate: AMA |publisher=Workplaceinfo.com.au |date=2012-03-20 |accessdate=2013-01-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.medicalobserver.com.au/news/doctors-certificate-questioned-after-mp-skips-parliament |title=Doctor’s certificate questioned after MP skips parliament |publisher=Medical Observer |date=2012-03-19 |accessdate=2013-01-10}}</ref>) is a statement from a [[physician]] or other [[health care provider]] that attests to the result of a [[physical examination|medical examination]] of a patient.<ref name="Ashtekar2001">{{cite book|author=S. Ashtekar|title=Health and Healing: A Manual of Primary Health Care|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=F0wYJXsHBIAC&pg=PA576|accessdate=10 January 2013|date=1 January 2001|publisher=Orient Blackswan|isbn=978-81-250-1624-3|pages=576–}}</ref> It can serve as a "sick note" (documentation that an employee is unfit for work) or evidence of a health condition.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.workplaceinfo.com.au/payroll/payroll-management/medical-certificates |title=Medical certificates |publisher=Workplaceinfo.com.au |date= |accessdate=2013-01-10}}</ref>

An '''aegrotat''' ({{IPAc-en|icon|'|iː|g|r|oʊ|t|æ|t|}}; {{etymology|la|aegrotat|he/she is ill}})<ref>
{{cite book
  | last = 
