  | year = 1998
  | location = Oxford, UK
  | isbn = 019861263X
}}</ref> or '''sick note''' is a type of medical certificate excusing a student's absence from school for reasons of [[illness]].

==Purpose and applications==
Medical certificates are sometimes required to obtain certain [[Health insurance|health benefits]] from an employer, make an insurance [[Cause of action|claim]], for tax purposes, or for certain legal procedures. Medical certificates are used to indicate eligibility of activity, such as the use of [[Disabled parking permit|disabled parking]]. Medical certificates can also be used to describe a medical condition a person has, such as blindness. Medical certificates are often used to certify that someone is free of [[Infectious disease|contagious diseases]], [[Substance dependence|drug addiction]], [[Mental disorder|mental illness]], or other health issues.

Health criteria are often required when making an application for something, such as an [[eye examination]] to get a driver's license. Other times medical criteria are presented voluntarily by an applicant in a self-assessment, without either a doctor or access to the person's [[medical record]]. Specific health criteria or medical history are required for certain jobs.

In the United States, the majority of [[Aviator|pilots]] are required to possess a valid medical certificate that certifies sound health as part of the requirements for piloting an [[Fixed-wing aircraft|airplane]].<ref name="Pilot'sHandbook">{{cite book |title=Pilot's Handbook of Aeronautical Knowledge |last=U.S. Department of Transportation, Federal Aviation Administration |first= |authorlink= |coauthors= |year=2009 |publisher=Government Printing Office |location= |isbn=0160823676 |page=16-2 |pages= |url=http://books.google.com/?id=0l8WO6Drz50C&pg=SA16-PA2&dq=medical+certificate#v=onepage&q=medical%20certificate&f=false |accessdate=January 2013}}</ref> In the U.S., [[Pilot certification in the United States#Sport pilot|sport pilots]] may use a valid state driver's license in place of a medical certificate, and [[Glider (aircraft)|glider]] and [[hot air balloon]] pilots are not required to obtain them.<ref name="Pilot'sHandbook"/>

==Aegrotat==
The term ''aegrotat'' (abbreviated as ''aegrot'') is used primarily in the [[United Kingdom]] and [[Commonwealth of Nations]]. In the context of [[British undergraduate degree classification|British undergraduate degrees]] a student who is too ill to finish may be awarded an aegrotat degree if the student otherwise would have passed exams or other requirements.

==Impact on occupation==
Except in certain unique circumstances, a holder of a medical certificate in the National Aeronautics and Space Administration may not "act as pilot in command or in any other capacity as a required flight crewmember of an aircraft".<ref>{{Cite journal | url = http://books.google.com/?id=7cg5AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA148&dq=%22medical+certificate%22#v=onepage&q=%22medical%20certificate%22&f=false | title = The Code of Federal Regulations of the United States of America | author1 = Staff | first1 = National Aeronautics and Space Administration | pages = 12 | year = 1982}}</ref>

A patient with conditions such as: measles, chicken-pox, hepititas A, leprousy, typhoid fever, and whooping cough, can return to work immediately after their healing phase or medical tests. Almost always the patient may only be allowed to return to work upon submission of a medical certificate.<ref>{{cite book | url=http://books.google.com.au/books?id=M1HOA3sCXNkC&pg=PA487&dq=%22medical+certificate%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=1sHvUOWGA4aiiAel5oCgCw&ved=0CEgQ6AEwAjgK#v=onepage&q=%22medical%20certificate%22&f=false | title=Manual Of Community Nursing and Communicable Diseases | accessdate=January 11, 2013 | pages=487}}</ref>

