==Eligibility==
Sometimes, there are standards and procedures in place, for workers in a certain field to be eligible to receive a medical certificate. Any airman at the National Aeronautics and Space Administration must give their employees access to the National Driver Register. On top of this, other tests which are required for first-, second- and third-class airmen are: eye, ear/nose/throat/equilibrium, mental, neurologic, and cardiovascular.<ref>{{Cite journal | url = http://books.google.com/?id=7cg5AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA148&dq=%22medical+certificate%22#v=onepage&q=%22medical%20certificate%22&f=false | title = The Code of Federal Regulations of the United States of America | author1 = Staff | first1 = National Aeronautics and Space Administration | pages = 67 | year = 1982}}</ref>

''The India List and India Office List 1905'' explains that officers on "Long Leave in Europe" must, among other things, provide a medical certificate, which is obtained at the Medical Board of India Office.<ref>{{cite book | url=http://books.google.com.au/books?id=3VQTAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA262&dq=%22medical+certificate%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=o8HvUK_2GpDBiQfyr4GIDA&ved=0CGMQ6AEwBg#v=onepage&q=%22medical%20certificate%22&f=false | title=The India List and India Office List | accessdate=January 11, 2013 | pages=262}}</ref>

''Practical Guide to Employees' State Insurance Act, Rules and Regulations'' explains that under the ESI Act, the empoyee must obtain a medical certificate via the ESI Dispensary/Hospital, which then gets deposited at the nearest office of the ESI Corporation.<ref>{{cite book | url=http://books.google.com.au/books?id=couYMu1aa5oC&pg=PA275&dq=%22medical+certificate%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=o8HvUK_2GpDBiQfyr4GIDA&ved=0CGgQ6AEwBw#v=onepage&q=%22medical%20certificate%22&f=false | title=Practical Guide to Employees' State Insurance Act, Rules and Regulations | accessdate=January 11, 2013 | pages=126}}</ref>

==Falsification==
As many illnesses can come about suddenly, sometimes the worker will not have enough time to receive a medical certificate, or may be too sick to obtain one. In other cases, the worker may not be bothered to go to the trouble of getting one, or may be lying about their illness and want to falsify a certificate to back up their story to their boss.

There have been discussions regarding whether it is okay to fire someone for submitting a fabricated medical certificates.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.mk.com.au/publications/article/sacked-for-submitting-false-medical-certificates-fair | title=Sacked for Submitting False Medical Certificates - Fair? | accessdate=January 11, 2013}}</ref> In many cases, it is deemed wrong, such as in Australia where a bank officer was dismissed after handing in a forged certificate, which prompted a Fair Work Australia Commissioner to say they had a "continued lack of regard for the truth".<ref>{{cite web | url=http://blog.vecci.org.au/2012/02/16/employee-sacked-for-creating-false-medical-certificate/ | title=Employee sacked for creating false medical certificate | accessdate=January 11, 2013}}</ref> Another example is a WA police officer who was stood down after committing the same offense.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.watoday.com.au/wa-news/officer-stood-down-for-allegedly-forging-medical-certificate-20081218-713y.html | title=Officer stood down for allegedly forging medical certificate| date=December 18, 2008 | accessdate=January 11, 2013}}</ref> Sometimes it is not so black and white. In one case, a woman claimed she was "coerced into falsifying [a] medical certificate [which ultimately led to her being fired] because she was 'being bullied and treated unfairly' by two managers".<ref>{{cite web | url=http://aworkcovervictimsdiary.com/2012/09/sacked-worker-forged-medical-certificate-claimed-nearly-died-way-treated/ | title=Sacked worker forged medical certificate and claimed she nearly died because the way she was treated | accessdate=January 11, 2013}}</ref>

There are some companies that sell fake medical certificates.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.doctorsnotestore.com/australia_fake_medical_certificate.html | title=Australian Sick Notes & Medical Certificates | accessdate=January 11, 2013}}</ref> Although the site ''Doctors Note Store'' sells "fake sick notes and medical certificates for workers in Australia, New Zealand and the United Kingdom", they add that the "fakes are for 'novelty use only'".<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.workplaceinfo.com.au/payroll/leave/ama-warns-over-fake-sick-notes | title=AMA warns over fake sick notes | accessdate=January 11, 2013}}</ref>

At Flinders University, "providing a forged medical certificate" is viewed as academic misconduct.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.flinders.edu.au/current-students/policies-procs/rights/important-changes.cfm | title=Important Changes to the University’s Student Policies and Procedures | accessdate=January 11, 2013}}</ref>

In New South Wales, medical professionals who "deliberately issue a false, misleading or inaccurate certificate" can be charged under the Medical Practice Act. This is in response to The New South Wales Medical Board "receiving numerous complaints from employers, insurers, the courts, etc regarding the quality, accuracy and truthfulness of sickness certificates".<ref name="MCP">{{cite web | url=http://www.mcnsw.org.au/page/old-policies/medical-certificates-policy/ | title=Medical Certificates Policy | page = 67 accessdate=January 11, 2013}}</ref>

==Validation==
In order to prove that one's medical certificate is authentic, the following should be done and taken into consideration<ref name="MCP"/>:

* Having it written in legible text, in the doctor's handwriting, and without "abbreviations or medical jargon".
* Should only include facts or observations made by the doctor, and each should be justified.
* Should include the date of appointment, how sick the patient is, the date they can go back to work, be addressed to the recipient of the certificate (boss etc.),
* Should only be for something "observed by the doctor" or "reported by the patient and deemed to be true by the doctor".
* Can be issued after the patient has taken sick leave, but it must include the date of appointment, and the length of time the employee should be out of work for.
* Should consider if the patient can return to work before they have fully healed, but with "altered duties".
* Respect "rights to confidentiality" and consent of patient (sometimes, the reason for sick leave may be personal and the patient may request it taken off the certificate, in which case "it should be made clear to the patient that the information provided on the certificate may not be sufficient to attract sick leave and that an employer has the ultimate right to accept or to reject a certificate".
* Falsifying a medical certificate is a form of fraud.

